06165nam a22009975i 9780813537733DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20052005nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135377337 a10.36019/97808135377332doi  a(DE-B1597)529196  a(OCoLC)68625153  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aE184.7b.W48 2005 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a305.896073/0071100aWhite Scholars/African American Texts /ced. by Lisa Long. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat makes someone an authority? What makes one person's knowledge more credible than another's? In the ongoing debates over racial authenticity, some attest that we can know each other's experiences simply because we are all "human," while others assume a more skeptical stance, insisting that racial differences create unbridgeable gaps in knowledge. Bringing new perspectives to these perennial debates, the essays in this collection explore the many difficulties created by the fact that white scholars greatly outnumber black scholars in the study and teaching of African American literature. Contributors, including some of the most prominent theorists in the field as well as younger scholars, examine who is speaking, what is being spoken and what is not, and why framing African American literature in terms of an exclusive black/white racial divide is problematic and limiting. In highlighting the "whiteness" of some African Americanists, the collection does not imply that the teaching or understanding of black literature by white scholars is definitively impossible. Indeed such work is not only possible, but imperative. Instead, the essays aim to open a much needed public conversation about the real and pressing challenges that white scholars face in this type of work, as well as the implications of how these challenges are met.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoriography. 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aAfrican AmericansxStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxStudy and teaching. 0aEducation, HigherxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aTeachers, WhitexUnited States. 0aTeachers, WhitezUnited States. 0aWhite peoplezUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 0aWhitesxIntellectual lifexUnited States. 0aWhiteszUnited StatesxIntellectual life. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAndrews, William L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Barbara A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Dale M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastronovo, Russ, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiwengo, Ngwarsungu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConley Kilinski, April, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnor, Kimberly Rae, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErnest, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKumar, Nita N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawrence, Amanda M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevine, Robert S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Leslie W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLong